so, you know, get ready.

00:09:28.660 --> 00:09:29.960
It's not going to be as fast.

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:31.800
I mean I'm doing one a year.

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:36.850
But having done that for so
long, I got a little bit,

00:09:36.850 --> 00:09:41.100
I wouldn't say bored, because I
always love Clarice, but it's a lot

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:42.770
of work doing other
things, you know,

00:09:42.770 --> 00:09:45.070
I have real job besides
doing Clarice.

00:09:45.070 --> 00:09:47.370
It's been more than
12 years of this.

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:53.770
And she -- the thing about
working with a truly great artist,

00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:55.500
or truly great writer, is
there is always more to say,

00:09:55.500 --> 00:09:58.080
and when I was writing
the introduction to this,

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:00.300
I thought haven't I already
said everything about her?

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:01.660
But it turns out I hadn't.

00:10:01.660 --> 00:10:06.850
And working through these stories
in this way, from her first story

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:09.840
that she publishes when she's 19
years old, and she's a student

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:12.630
to the stories that leaves
incomplete as sketches

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:16.980
on her death bed, which are
very fantastic stories too,

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:20.950
you see this entire woman's life
being written out in her life,

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:24.120
throughout her life, but
also writing about how women,

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:26.610
specifically change and grow.

00:10:26.610 --> 00:10:29.490
And so I wrote a little
thing about this.

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:32.990 position:56%
I discovered this was the first time
a woman had ever done this anywhere,

00:10:32.990 --> 00:10:38.460
and this is -- if you are
familiar with feminist criticism,

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:41.460
this is something that comes
up a lot, especially, you know,

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:44.760
in the '60's and the
'70's when female cultural

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:46.880
and intellectual achievement
is starting to be reevaluated

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.460
and starting to be brought
out of the gutter, you know,

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:52.330
where it was always relegated
because it was women.

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:54.630
Even Virginia Woolf,
until the '70's,

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:58.980
was not considered good
enough to be on any curriculum

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:00.540
in this country or in England.

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:03.570
And so there was this work
for two or three generations

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:09.140
of female scholars who brought this
out of the closet and discovered.

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:12.610
But one of the questions was
why had it not happened before.

00:11:12.610 --> 00:11:16.680
So I thought why it's interesting.

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:20.660
She comes from an absolutely
destitute background.

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:23.720
She comes from really
the dredges of society.

00:11:23.720 --> 00:11:28.250
I mean she comes from a very poor,
not even an immigrant background

00:11:28.250 --> 00:11:32.170 position:56%
but a refugee background, and she
becomes by the time she's a teenager

00:11:32.170 --> 00:11:35.830
and she's writing this
story, she becomes famous as,

00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:39.110
in the literary world of
Rio, but she becomes famous

00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:42.480
as not only the most beautiful
girl in Rio de Janeiro,

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:45.360
which was something, you
know, it's an accomplishment,

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:50.510
but also this woman that
everybody knew was a genius.

00:11:50.510 --> 00:11:53.200 position:56%
And so I wrote this thing about her.

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:56.360
I'll just read it briefly,
and then we can talk about it.

00:11:56.360 --> 00:12:00.530
This achievement -- oh,
okay, so "The other side

00:12:00.530 --> 00:12:04.390
of silence is speech," and
there are a lot of silent women

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:07.850
in these stories, women who can't
speak or who are silent forcibly

00:12:07.850 --> 00:12:10.390
by circumstances or by men.

00:12:10.390 --> 00:12:15.260 position:56%
"Today women as writers and women
as the subjects of women writers are

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:18.250
so familiar that it is hard to
believe that Clarice's respect

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:22.350
of characters or their lives
ever needed to be discovered.

00:12:22.350 --> 00:12:25.780 position:56%
But to see this work from the
perspective of what came after it is

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:29.010
to miss it's historical novelty.

00:12:29.010 --> 00:12:31.820
Clarice was fundamentally
without a tradition.

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:34.930
She was an immigrant, and though
she had the ancient European Jewish

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:38.880
tradition behind her, that world,
particularly in the tiny shtetl

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:41.760
where she was born in
the western Ukraine,

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:45.090
was not easily adaptable
to modern urban lives.

00:12:45.090 --> 00:12:47.560
In the literature of
the language she wrote,

00:12:47.560 --> 00:12:50.660
the subject of modern
women no more existed

00:12:50.660 --> 00:12:52.400
than did woman writers themselves."

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:56.680
Now this is kind of amazing if you
think about what comes after it.

00:12:56.680 --> 00:12:57.980
There were a couple
of Brazilian women

00:12:57.980 --> 00:13:01.780
who had written Cecelia
Morales [phonetic] and,

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:04.790
