00:13:04.790 --> 00:13:09.040
And now I say, "In this respect
Portuguese was no different

00:13:09.040 --> 00:13:11.250
from any other language,
and Brazil was no different

00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:12.560
from any other country.

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:17.280
Clarice was 9 when Virginia Woolf
asked a question Clarice later

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:21.970
quoted, 'Who shall measure the heat
and violence of the poet's heart

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:24.870
when caught entangled
in a woman's body?'

00:13:24.870 --> 00:13:27.630
The question, Woolf believed,
applied as much to women

00:13:27.630 --> 00:13:31.620
of her own day as it did
to women of Shakespeare's.

00:13:31.620 --> 00:13:36.040
This novelty explains some of
the fascination and confusion

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:38.160
that early readers of
Hurricaine Clarice,"

00:13:38.160 --> 00:13:41.500
which is a title someone
gave her, a friend of hers,

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:45.050
"one imagines a similar thrill of
discovery among the first readers

00:13:45.050 --> 00:13:49.590
of Dickens and [inaudible] when
literature first cast it's light

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:53.340
on the working classes or when
gay readers first saw their lives

00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:54.640
written about sympathetically

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:58.910
or when colonial people exchanged
the condescension of folklore

00:13:58.910 --> 00:14:01.490
for the higher dignity
of literature.

00:14:01.490 --> 00:14:04.260
The astonishment her achievement
provoked is still palpable

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:07.060
in the yellowing scrapbooks
preserving the reviews

00:14:07.060 --> 00:14:09.760
in Clarice Lispector's archives."

00:14:09.760 --> 00:14:14.640
And so I want to just talk,
follow up about this a little bit

00:14:14.640 --> 00:14:16.280
