has liked animals

00:56:22.710 --> 00:56:26.070
because she had been often
disappointed by people,

00:56:26.070 --> 00:56:29.880
which is something we've
all been familiar with.

00:56:29.880 --> 00:56:31.180
She not the only one?

00:56:31.180 --> 00:56:35.340
And, so she loves animals
because they were physical,

00:56:35.340 --> 00:56:39.080
and they were warm, and they
were, and they didn't think.

00:56:39.080 --> 00:56:41.530
I think that's maybe really
an important part of animals.

00:56:41.530 --> 00:56:42.830
And music too.

00:56:42.830 --> 00:56:44.130
You know, music doesn't have words.

00:56:44.130 --> 00:56:47.870
I mean it can have words, but what
makes the music music is the sound,

00:56:47.870 --> 00:56:49.170
not the words.

00:56:49.170 --> 00:56:55.460
And she, as part of the idea
of getting beyond thought

00:56:55.460 --> 00:56:58.890
and getting beyond these kind
of constructions of ourselves.

00:56:58.890 --> 00:57:01.560
That she was just really
not interested,

00:57:01.560 --> 00:57:03.280
and I think she saw through that.

00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:04.580
She thought that was a tool.

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:05.950
You know, just like clothing.

00:57:05.950 --> 00:57:07.250
And she was a feminine, you know,

00:57:07.250 --> 00:57:09.020
as they say in Brazil,
a feminine columnist.

00:57:09.020 --> 00:57:12.390
She wrote about makeup and
hair and clothes for years,

00:57:12.390 --> 00:57:14.250
every day in the papers in Rio.

00:57:14.250 --> 00:57:18.710
So she knew how women were
supposed to look or men.

00:57:18.710 --> 00:57:22.730
She wrote advice about how to use
perfume and how to use mascara,

00:57:22.730 --> 00:57:24.590
which is hilarious if you
know anything about her.

00:57:24.590 --> 00:57:27.890
I mean she's like the
most radical thinker,

00:57:27.890 --> 00:57:31.000
I think probably the most radial
thinker of the 20th century.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:34.990
Like when you think about,
like the existentialists,

00:57:34.990 --> 00:57:37.000
I would maybe accept [inaudible],
but some of these people

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.840
like [inaudible] and oh,
I mean it's so boring

00:57:39.840 --> 00:57:42.700 position:56%
and over thought after you read her.

00:57:42.700 --> 00:57:46.280
You know, she's, and that's why
I quote in the very beginning

00:57:46.280 --> 00:57:51.400 position:56%
of the biography this whole cabalist
in the 13th century who gets

00:57:51.400 --> 00:57:53.950
in Spain somewhere very
upset with these people.

00:57:53.950 --> 00:57:56.680
He's like, ah, you
know, you ought to know.

00:57:56.680 --> 00:58:01.380
But, you know, we begin,
no where you end, we begin,

00:58:01.380 --> 00:58:05.770
speaking to the philosophers.

00:58:05.770 --> 00:58:07.830
Mystics are not philosophers.

00:58:07.830 --> 00:58:10.360
They're, they're beyond that.

00:58:12.510 --> 00:58:13.810
&gt;&gt; So when --

00:58:13.810 --> 00:58:15.110
&gt;&gt; I'm sorry, just [inaudible] --

00:58:15.110 --> 00:58:16.410
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:58:16.410 --> 00:58:21.400
&gt;&gt; A couple years before she died,
she gave [inaudible] TV interview,

00:58:21.400 --> 00:58:25.580
and you probably saw that.

00:58:25.580 --> 00:58:26.880
&gt;&gt; I subtitled it.

00:58:26.880 --> 00:58:29.140
&gt;&gt; You did?

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:31.860
[laughter] She was
kind of really for me,

00:58:31.860 --> 00:58:35.040
she looked really sad, you know.

00:58:35.040 --> 00:58:36.340
The last time.

00:58:36.340 --> 00:58:38.290
And then she said, I
don't understand myself.

00:58:38.290 --> 00:58:39.590
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:58:39.590 --> 00:58:42.320
&gt;&gt; Yeah. She said that of all
of the books that she wrote,

00:58:42.320 --> 00:58:43.870
I don't understand what they say.

00:58:43.870 --> 00:58:46.570
&gt;&gt; Clarice was very
fakely modest oftentimes.

00:58:46.570 --> 00:58:48.590
She knew exactly who she was.

00:58:48.590 --> 00:58:51.320 position:56%
Just like you think didn't Emily
Dickinson probably know who she was?

00:58:51.320 --> 00:58:52.620
She must have.

00:58:52.620 --> 00:58:54.250
You know, you can't have
that level of thinking.

00:58:54.250 --> 00:58:57.770
That video was not a couple
of years before she died,

00:58:57.770 --> 00:58:59.710 position:56%
it was a few months before she died.

00:58:59.710 --> 00:59:02.230
She was dying when she
gave that interview,

00:59:02.230 --> 00:59:03.530
which was a great interview,

00:59:03.530 --> 00:59:07.270
because it was the only time
she ever spoke on television.

00:59:07.270 --> 00:59:11.120
And fascinatingly enough,
that interview was something,

00:59:11.120 --> 00:59:15.840 position:56%
she was interviewed by a
journalist, and he actually went mad

00:59:15.840 --> 00:59:17.540
after that interview,
in a certain way.

00:59:17.540 --> 00:59:18.840
I spoke to him.

00:59:18.840 --> 00:59:21.600
He was a little bit crazy at the
end of his life, but all because of

00:59:21.600 --> 00:59:25.260
that interview, and he had
this thing, he said once to me,

00:59:25.260 --> 00:59:29.580
he said neither Kafka nor
Rudolf [phonetic] would ever

00:59:29.580 --> 00:59:30.880
be interviewed.

00:59:30.880 --> 00:59:33.800
I had her, and I fucked it up.

00:59:34.910 --> 00:59:36.530
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:59:36.530 --> 00:59:40.690
&gt;&gt; So he felt the weight of
this historic responsibility,

00:59:40.690 --> 00:59:43.020
and actually his interview,
she shows up.

00:59:43.020 --> 00:59:44.430
She was visiting San Paolo.

00:59:44.430 --> 00:59:46.140
She was in the studio
with her friend, Olga,

00:59:46.140 --> 00:59:49.010 position:56%
who was one of her companions at the
end of her life and would take her

00:59:49.010 --> 00:59:52.980
around and put her in a taxi
and all this, and she walked

00:59:52.980 --> 00:59:56.400
into [foreign language], which was
the old sort of PBS or whatever

00:59:56.400 --> 00:59:58.570
of Brazil, and she
walked through the door,

00:59:58.570 --> 01:00:00.650
and she said you can
interview me now.

01:00:00.650 --> 01:00:03.270
And she was like the most
famous writer in Brazil,

01:00:03.270 --> 01:00:07.140 position:56%
and she had famously never been
interviewed, and she just walked in,

01:00:07.140 --> 01:00:08.620
and she said okay I'm ready.

01:00:08.620 --> 01:00:12.670
And there was total panic,
and everybody ran to try

01:00:12.670 --> 01:00:16.450 position:56%
to get her a studio and get her a
thing and you know and find this guy

01:00:16.450 --> 01:00:18.970 position:56%
who was like, I don't know,
smoking a cigarette or eating lunch,

01:00:18.970 --> 01:00:24.250
and he said, you know, come on
Clarice, and it's fascinating

01:00:24.250 --> 01:00:27.020
that interview is so powerful
because everybody who's seen it,

01:00:27.020 --> 01:00:31.650
I just sent it to Holland last
night for a television thing,

01:00:31.650 --> 01:00:35.090
and the woman who watched it was
amazed she'd never seen it before,

01:00:35.090 --> 01:00:39.620
the power that comes
out of this dying woman,

01:00:39.620 --> 01:00:50.440
and that's why I think every
Brazilian has seen that, you know,

01:00:50.440 --> 01:00:55.090
because it's so unforgettable.

01:00:55.090 --> 01:00:57.660
It's a powerful thing.

01:00:57.660 --> 01:01:08.800
&gt;&gt; I think we have, we'll take one
more question, and then we'll --

01:01:08.800 --> 01:01:17.020
&gt;&gt; Sorry, I'm a little
under the weather.

01:01:17.020 --> 01:01:30.320
I wanted to do a little bit more
about the role of religion in her,

01:01:30.320 --> 01:01:37.320
you know, in her writing, for
her, and I don't even know how

01:01:37.320 --> 01:01:42.400
to formulate this question, but
it's very curious to me, you know,

01:01:42.400 --> 01:01:50.030
about being Jewish and [inaudible]
her books are so autobiographical

01:01:50.030 --> 01:01:54.260
for me that you see different
factors and different directions

01:01:54.260 --> 01:01:55.840
that she goes about [inaudible].

01:01:55.840 --> 01:01:58.970
&gt;&gt; Well so Clarice comes
from a rabbinical family.

01:01:58.970 --> 01:02:05.050
She comes from -- this is obvious
if you know Jews, and if you know

01:02:05.050 --> 01:02:08.730
where Jews come from,
especially in terms of class

01:02:08.730 --> 01:02:15.210
and education background, these
things go, as they did in Europe,

01:02:15.210 --> 01:02:17.890
they went from generation
to generation,

01:02:17.890 --> 01:02:21.090
and the rabbinical families
were the same people.

01:02:21.090 --> 01:02:24.210
And she comes from
those, that background.

01:02:24.210 --> 01:02:28.530
And what happens to her at the
very beginning of the book,

01:02:28.530 --> 01:02:36.080
I tell the story, the disaster that
happens to her family that happened

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:43.570
to hundreds of thousands of
Jews after the First World War,

01:02:43.570 --> 01:02:45.930
even before the Second World
War, which was even worse,

01:02:45.930 --> 01:02:50.210
but hundreds of thousands
of people killed.

01:02:50.210 --> 01:02:53.130
Her grandfather was murdered.

01:02:53.130 --> 01:02:58.020
Her mother was raped and got
syphilis and died in Brazil.

01:02:58.020 --> 01:03:01.580
All of their being nice
to God didn't work.

01:03:01.580 --> 01:03:02.880
This is the point.

01:03:02.880 --> 01:03:11.590
All of the 613 commandments and
the, you know, do three dances

01:03:11.590 --> 01:03:14.130
around the Magilla
[phonetic], and all this kind

01:03:14.130 --> 01:03:15.430
of stuff, complete failure.

01:03:15.430 --> 01:03:16.730
Nothing about that.

01:03:16.730 --> 01:03:18.190
And these were religious people.

01:03:18.190 --> 01:03:23.570
They were forced to see the failure
of this human-centered existence,

01:03:23.570 --> 01:03:27.410
or this human-centered idea of God,

01:03:27.410 --> 01:03:31.520
which is that God is this
basically benevolent guy,

01:03:31.520 --> 01:03:36.580
who if you do certain things,
like if you clean out the crumbs

01:03:36.580 --> 01:03:40.850
from your pantry in April,
and if you, you know,

01:03:40.850 --> 01:03:43.320
cut the foreskin off
your kid, you know,

01:03:43.320 --> 01:03:47.850
then basically God is going piece,
sort of like a touchy parent,

01:03:47.850 --> 01:03:56.450
you know, but it's basically
an idea of God as a human

01:03:56.450 --> 01:04:01.470
that can be pleased or
displeased, and he can get mad.

01:04:01.470 --> 01:04:04.080
And he'll be happy if
you do this or that,

01:04:04.080 --> 01:04:05.380
so you have to do these
little dances.

01:04:05.380 --> 01:04:06.680
That's a ridiculous thought.

01:04:06.680 --> 01:04:10.940
I mean it's a ridiculous thought
even as I'm formulating it now

01:04:10.940 --> 01:04:12.240
because it actually is ridiculous.

01:04:12.240 --> 01:04:13.540
It is not the reality
of anybody's life.

01:04:13.540 --> 01:04:14.840
And it's not the reality of
physics or astronomy or anything.

01:04:14.840 --> 01:04:16.540
And yet, what's so fascinating
about her is the spiritual impulse

01:04:16.540 --> 01:04:17.840
as opposed to the religious
impulse is still there,

01:04:17.840 --> 01:04:19.600
and it's 100 percent there, and
it's not just there in a way

01:04:19.600 --> 01:04:20.900
that is some kind of legacy.

01:04:20.900 --> 01:04:22.200
If this is my family, used to be
in clothing, so I love a good suit.

01:04:22.200 --> 01:04:23.500
You know, it's not like that.

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:24.800
It's something really deep, and
she uses this expression not

01:04:24.800 --> 01:04:26.110
to ridicule religion but to find
some other spiritual values,

01:04:26.110 --> 01:04:27.520
and she finds them where the
Jews have always found them,

01:04:27.520 --> 01:04:29.260
which was in language, and that's
I think what you feel of the beauty

01:04:29.260 --> 01:04:30.790
if you read her, especially if
you read her in her own language.

01:04:30.790 --> 01:04:32.230
And so, of course it's something
she regretted losing that,

01:04:32.230 --> 01:04:33.530
because it's comforting to believe

01:04:33.530 --> 01:04:34.830
that if you just do these certain
things and everybody's happy

01:04:34.830 --> 01:04:36.130
and you don't get cancer, but
of course you do get cancer,

01:04:36.130 --> 01:04:37.430
and you do die, and you
do suffer horrible things.

01:04:37.430 --> 01:04:38.950
Your child can go mad, and your
mother can die, and these things --

01:04:38.950 --> 01:04:40.250
so it's a very complicated thing,

01:04:40.250 --> 01:04:41.550
but it actually becomes
more beautiful

01:04:41.550 --> 01:04:42.850
because the hocus pocus
gets taken away from it,

01:04:42.850 --> 01:04:44.150
and what you have is this desire
to connect with something divine.

01:04:44.150 --> 01:04:45.450
And she does.

01:04:45.450 --> 01:04:46.750
So, on that note --

